1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:28,200
 Thank you very much, Governor Vujicic, dear Boris. On behalf of all of us, thank you for a wonderful evening. It was such a fantastic mixture of history and culture. And thank you for working hard to secure good weather.

2
00:00:30,000 --> 00:00:50,000
 Before I get into my speech, I want to recognize the work of the two teams, the IMF and the creation team, for organizing this conference. And I suggest we give these guys a round of applause. Thank you.

3
00:00:56,000 --> 00:01:24,000
 It is fantastic to be with you again. I am particularly pleased that this time, the Commission wisely allowed Valdis Dombrovskis to be here. Last time, he was sent as an ambassador to an inauguration, if I remember correctly. I can say that listening to you last evening,

4
00:01:24,000 --> 00:01:39,000
 gave me a very high degree of confidence that this time it will be different. This time Europe will stand up for itself, for its citizens, and for the betterment of the whole world.

5
00:01:39,000 --> 00:02:08,000
 We are together at the time of higher uncertainty. The fog over our heads is actually thicker. And that makes it even more important to compare notes and see through this uncertainty and make the best out of the opportunities challenge always presents.

6
00:02:08,000 --> 00:02:31,000
 I want to start before I get into the challenges. I want to reflect on the successes this region has achieved. We have had three remarkable decades of reforms promoting economic openness and integration.

7
00:02:31,000 --> 00:02:32,000
 We have had three remarkable decades of reforms in the future. We have had three remarkable decades of the future.

8
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:32,000
 We have had three remarkable decades of the future. We have had three remarkable decades of the future.

9
00:02:32,000 --> 00:02:33,000
 We have had three remarkable decades of the future. We have had three remarkable decades of the future.

10
00:02:33,000 --> 00:02:34,000
 We have had three remarkable decades of the future. We have had three remarkable decades of the future.

11
00:02:34,000 --> 00:03:01,000
 And then, for some, for some within the EU as member states, for others within the EU family as candidate countries. And we should not underestimate how significant that step towards enlarging the European family, these steps, one after another, have been.

12
00:03:01,000 --> 00:03:30,000
 As Boris reminded us, this has led to significant convergence of countries with their better-off peers. Since the mid-90s, incomes have more than doubled. And the gap relative to the advanced Europe has shrunk sharply.

13
00:03:30,000 --> 00:03:41,080
 Manufacturing became a catalyst for productivity growth as integration into European and global

14
00:03:41,080 --> 00:03:52,120
 value chains helped the CEE economies reach beyond their domestic markets.

15
00:03:52,120 --> 00:03:59,060
 And at the same time, openness to foreign direct investment accelerated capital accumulation

16
00:03:59,060 --> 00:04:01,480
 and technology transfer.

17
00:04:01,480 --> 00:04:09,460
 And of course, EU accession played and continues to play a huge role.

18
00:04:09,460 --> 00:04:16,140
 Powered by domestic structural reforms put in place on the path to EU accession, countries

19
00:04:16,140 --> 00:04:23,400
 that have joined the EU, accelerated their income convergence with advanced Europe, and

20
00:04:23,400 --> 00:04:28,120
 outperformed comparable countries outside of the bloc.

21
00:04:28,120 --> 00:04:33,540
 So, what is the conclusion so far?

22
00:04:33,540 --> 00:04:35,540
 Well done.

23
00:04:35,540 --> 00:04:40,620
 Second, well, we have also unfinished business.

24
00:04:40,620 --> 00:04:43,540
 The journey is far, far from being completed.

25
00:04:43,540 --> 00:04:50,960
 One thing that we have observed with a little bit of sadness is very often, if not always,

26
00:04:50,960 --> 00:04:57,960
 when countries join the European Union, the drive for reform eases somewhat.

27
00:04:57,960 --> 00:05:04,380
 I was just talking to our friend from Moldova, saying, look, why are you an accession country?

28
00:05:04,380 --> 00:05:05,380
 Step on the pedal.

29
00:05:05,380 --> 00:05:10,380
 Because once you get in, there would be this natural tendency to say, oh, thank God we are

30
00:05:10,380 --> 00:05:11,380
 in.

31
00:05:11,380 --> 00:05:12,380
 We can relax.

32
00:05:12,380 --> 00:05:13,800
 We can relax.

33
00:05:13,800 --> 00:05:14,800
 But relax we cannot.

34
00:05:14,800 --> 00:05:24,880
 We have to recognize that after the global financial crisis, we have seen a drop in investment, and

35
00:05:24,880 --> 00:05:31,800
 this has contributed to a productivity slump that has only worsened after COVID.

36
00:05:31,800 --> 00:05:37,220
 Revitalizing reforms is absolutely paramount.

37
00:05:37,220 --> 00:05:49,220
 We see how we are being affected by tightness of our labor markets, by high energy costs, by the

38
00:05:49,220 --> 00:05:59,060
 fact that technology is moving very fast, and if we are not moving even faster, we risk to

39
00:05:59,060 --> 00:06:00,060
 to fall behind.

40
00:06:00,060 --> 00:06:13,360
 So we -- I would really urge us to be ambitious to pursue reforms, and to do it because, on top

41
00:06:13,360 --> 00:06:19,760
 of everything, we are now faced with huge new challenges.

42
00:06:19,760 --> 00:06:29,040
 The sweeping disruptions to the world trade system are plain for everybody to

43
00:06:29,040 --> 00:06:34,360
 to see, the way we function is being tested.

44
00:06:34,360 --> 00:06:45,160
 And while most of the countries in this room are less impacted directly by U.S. tariffs,

45
00:06:45,160 --> 00:06:53,100
 let us be very clear, the indirect impact is significant as these disruptions pose a major

46
00:06:53,100 --> 00:06:58,420
 threat to the region's main trading partners.

47
00:06:58,420 --> 00:07:05,720
 And to the overall economic model that Boris described so well, small, open economies need

48
00:07:05,720 --> 00:07:11,280
 trade to improve the well-being of their people.

49
00:07:11,280 --> 00:07:18,100
 Trade tensions and uncertainty complicate domestic and foreign investment plans, and this is particularly

50
00:07:18,100 --> 00:07:26,420
 very painful for a region that needs access to modern production processes, needs more jobs

51
00:07:26,420 --> 00:07:35,420
 in high productivity sectors, and needs this open world to expand economic opportunities.

52
00:07:35,420 --> 00:07:40,740
 So what is my main message?

53
00:07:40,740 --> 00:07:49,800
 Standing still, taking shelter when the winds are blowing, hoping for the storm to pass is

54
00:07:49,800 --> 00:07:51,740
 not a plan.

55
00:07:51,740 --> 00:08:00,120
 Standing still, it would be much wiser to assume that many of the shifts we are witnessing

56
00:08:00,120 --> 00:08:05,060
 are here to state, that more storms are going to hit us.

57
00:08:05,060 --> 00:08:07,060
 So what do we do?

58
00:08:07,060 --> 00:08:20,740
 In a stormy weather, how can we actually turn the winds from a risk for our navigation to a

59
00:08:20,740 --> 00:08:31,540
 to a tailwind from, you call it the Adriatic border, make the Adriatic border work for us, for

60
00:08:31,540 --> 00:08:34,140
 our sail, not against it.

61
00:08:34,140 --> 00:08:39,540
 I want to point to three critical priorities.

62
00:08:39,540 --> 00:08:49,740
 First, steering a steady course in terms of macroeconomic policy, monetary and fiscal stability

63
00:08:49,740 --> 00:08:56,540
 as our most reliable means to deal with uncertainty.

64
00:08:56,540 --> 00:09:07,420
 Second, getting our ship in better order so it can move faster, and that means pursue structural

65
00:09:07,420 --> 00:09:08,540
 reforms for growth.

66
00:09:08,540 --> 00:09:16,540
 Third, integrate more deeply into and within the single market of the EU.

67
00:09:16,540 --> 00:09:21,340
 Strength through regional cooperation.

68
00:09:21,340 --> 00:09:25,340
 Let me briefly discuss each one of these points.

69
00:09:25,340 --> 00:09:32,140
 priority one, actions to mitigate uncertainty.

70
00:09:32,140 --> 00:09:38,140
 It is always important to have sound monetary policy, sound fiscal policy.

71
00:09:38,140 --> 00:09:44,140
 Even more important when uncertainty is higher.

72
00:09:44,140 --> 00:09:50,940
 I think economic and financial stability is the anchor on which you can build your plans.

73
00:09:50,940 --> 00:09:54,940
 I see some emerging risks there.

74
00:09:54,940 --> 00:10:01,740
 on the monetary policy side.

75
00:10:01,740 --> 00:10:05,740
 The pressure on central bank independence has become harder.

76
00:10:05,740 --> 00:10:09,740
 We all have a role to play to protect it.

77
00:10:09,740 --> 00:10:18,540
 I know that in the round table we had yesterday, this was a topic that came time and again.

78
00:10:18,540 --> 00:10:25,340
 We also recognize that on the fiscal front, how many of you are finance ministers and

79
00:10:25,340 --> 00:10:29,340
 those working in finance authorities?

80
00:10:29,340 --> 00:10:31,340
 Raise your hand.

81
00:10:31,340 --> 00:10:33,340
 Let me see.

82
00:10:33,340 --> 00:10:42,140
 How many are central bankers?

83
00:10:42,140 --> 00:10:44,140
 Very good central bankers this time.

84
00:10:44,140 --> 00:10:46,140
 I have an upper hand in this audience.

85
00:10:46,140 --> 00:10:54,140
 For the finance authorities, I am very keen to see central bankers staying united and making

86
00:10:54,140 --> 00:10:58,940
 a strong case for central bank independence for the fiscal authorities.

87
00:10:58,940 --> 00:11:02,940
 It is going to be a very tough time ahead of you.

88
00:11:02,940 --> 00:11:03,740
 Why?

89
00:11:03,740 --> 00:11:13,020
 Because over the last couple of years, what has happened is shock after shock after shock

90
00:11:13,020 --> 00:11:16,780
 forced more fiscal largeness.

91
00:11:16,780 --> 00:11:22,300
 They forced providing more support to household and to businesses.

92
00:11:22,860 --> 00:11:29,660
 The result, higher deficits, higher debt, but even more problematic,

93
00:11:29,660 --> 00:11:37,020
 businesses and households getting accustomed to that largeness.

94
00:11:37,020 --> 00:11:40,380
 And now we need to go for fiscal consolidation.

95
00:11:40,380 --> 00:11:46,220
 We have to say enough of this sugar rush, we have to do it differently.

96
00:11:46,220 --> 00:11:52,380
 While at the same time there are more pressures for defense, more pressures from climate, more

97
00:11:52,380 --> 00:11:53,980
 pressures for demography.

98
00:11:53,980 --> 00:11:59,420
 So I think that this is where the fund also can be very helpful.

99
00:11:59,420 --> 00:12:07,980
 So we can have fiscal policy that is prudent in terms of raising revenues, closing tax loopholes,

100
00:12:07,980 --> 00:12:11,980
 prudent in terms of improving the quality of spending.

101
00:12:13,260 --> 00:12:17,100
 Second priority, boost growth potential.

102
00:12:17,100 --> 00:12:19,900
 We have done a very interesting study.

103
00:12:19,900 --> 00:12:22,780
 I recommend to everybody here take a look.

104
00:12:22,780 --> 00:12:27,660
 It shows that this potential is quite significant.

105
00:12:27,660 --> 00:12:28,300
 Thank you.

106
00:12:28,300 --> 00:12:35,420
 For the first question, domestic reforms across the CC, let me say it simply.

107
00:12:35,420 --> 00:12:44,540
 The CC region could lift GDP levels by 7% over the medium term.

108
00:12:45,420 --> 00:12:49,980
 And for the Western Balkans, even more, by 9%.

109
00:12:49,980 --> 00:12:57,020
 Just imagine what you can do if you have that much more in terms of GDP.

110
00:12:57,020 --> 00:13:05,500
 And that you can only do if you are relentless, pursuing these reforms around the labor markets,

111
00:13:06,460 --> 00:13:12,060
 around the investment climate, around the governance performance.

112
00:13:12,060 --> 00:13:20,780
 And the third priority, last on my list, but definitely not least, work together.

113
00:13:20,780 --> 00:13:28,620
 Integration is the only way for our small economies to be stronger in a world of more frequent

114
00:13:28,620 --> 00:13:30,380
 and devastating shocks.

115
00:13:30,380 --> 00:13:39,900
 It has been a source of success for us, and it is still with huge potential.

116
00:13:39,900 --> 00:13:42,460
 I look at Valdis.

117
00:13:42,460 --> 00:13:53,020
 We need the European Union to become relentlessly ambitious to complete the single market.

118
00:13:53,980 --> 00:14:04,540
 At the IMF, we have done a study that shows that internal barriers among the 27 member states of the EU

119
00:14:04,540 --> 00:14:16,940
 are the equivalent of 44% tariffs for goods and 110% tariffs for services.

120
00:14:18,140 --> 00:14:23,660
 Obviously, this is in our hands to solve.

121
00:14:23,660 --> 00:14:32,940
 And I know that Valdis gets up in the morning, goes to bed thinking about it, Boris,

122
00:14:32,940 --> 00:14:41,580
 and working on it much harder than managing the exit of the UK from the European Union.

123
00:14:43,980 --> 00:14:57,500
 I, as a European, I see 2025 as a decisive year for the European Union and for the world.

124
00:14:57,500 --> 00:15:05,260
 Europe has a tremendous opportunity and responsibility to lead.

125
00:15:06,060 --> 00:15:14,220
 Europe is fantastic as a place that operates on the basis of rules,

126
00:15:14,220 --> 00:15:23,900
 where there is respect for each and every one of countries, big and small,

127
00:15:23,900 --> 00:15:34,300
 where there is a social capital built on the basis of our cooperation.

128
00:15:34,300 --> 00:15:43,260
 And I do hope we will see Europe raising to the challenge that is presented to us, the challenge to lead.

129
00:15:43,260 --> 00:15:51,660
 We have looked into concrete steps to do so, a more integrated electricity market,

130
00:15:51,660 --> 00:15:59,100
 more capital for start-ups, better labor mobility across borders, simpler regulation,

131
00:15:59,100 --> 00:16:03,500
 and, yes, capital markets union.

132
00:16:03,500 --> 00:16:12,860
 That, together, can bring tremendous benefit in terms of competitiveness for Europe

133
00:16:12,860 --> 00:16:19,180
 and can raise EU GDP by about 3% over the next 10 years.

134
00:16:20,220 --> 00:16:27,340
 I also would make, I was a commissioner for budget in my days in the European Union.

135
00:16:27,340 --> 00:16:35,900
 I also would put a word to Europe to think about the value of the collective.

136
00:16:35,900 --> 00:16:44,940
 And I would argue that the EU budget can lend more of a hand to Europe's transformation.

137
00:16:44,940 --> 00:16:53,100
 I know this is not an easy conversation, but at this time it is a paramount decision to be made,

138
00:16:53,100 --> 00:16:58,220
 to have that capacity to lift up Europe's potential.

139
00:16:59,340 --> 00:17:03,340
 So let me conclude in the following way.

140
00:17:03,340 --> 00:17:14,620
 Throughout history, there are moments that present incredible challenge,

141
00:17:14,620 --> 00:17:20,780
 but also moments of incredible opportunity, an opportunity not to be missed.

142
00:17:21,820 --> 00:17:23,420
 This is one of these moments.

143
00:17:23,420 --> 00:17:33,180
 And I so strongly believe that this region, and more broadly Europe,

144
00:17:33,180 --> 00:17:43,500
 is going to stand on its feet, meet what is expected from us at this moment in our history.

145
00:17:43,500 --> 00:17:49,580
 I'm not going to finish with Latin Boris, somebody has to break this tradition.

146
00:17:49,580 --> 00:17:57,340
 But I remember fondly how when I was here last time, it was your birthday and I sang for you.

147
00:17:57,340 --> 00:18:04,060
 And I'm going to finish by singing for everybody my favorite song of all times.

148
00:18:04,940 --> 00:18:07,180
 Very appropriate for the day.

149
00:18:07,180 --> 00:18:14,620
 And it is we will, we will rock you.

150
00:18:14,620 --> 00:18:22,300
 Thank you.

